shader_t* R_FindShader ( const char *  name,
shaderType_t  type,
qboolean  mipRawImage 
)

Will always return a valid shader, but it might be the default shader if the real one can't be found.

In the interest of not requiring an explicit shader text entry to be defined for every single image used in the game, three default shader behaviors can be auto-created for any image:

If type == SHADER_2D, then the image will be used for 2D rendering unless an explicit shader is found

If type == SHADER_3D_DYNAMIC, then the image will have dynamic diffuse lighting applied to it, as apropriate for most entity skin surfaces.

If type == SHADER_3D_STATIC, then the image will use the vertex rgba modulate values, as apropriate for misc_model pre-lit surfaces.

Definition at line 305 of file tr_shadows.c.

void RB_RenderFlares ( void  )

Because flares are simulating an occular effect, they should be drawn after everything (all views) in the entire frame has been drawn.

Because of the way portals use the depth buffer to mark off areas, the needed information would be lost after each view, so we are forced to draw flares after each view.

The resulting artifact is that flares in mirrors or portals don't dim properly when occluded by something in the main view, and portal flares that should extend past the portal edge will be overwritten.
